==Biopics==
* ''James Brown: The Man, the Message, the Music'' (1992), the first biopic about James Brown{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}
*''Mr. Dynamite: The Rise of James Brown'' (2014), released in April 2014, written and directed by Alex Gibney, produced by Mick Jagger.
* ''[[Get on Up (film)|Get on Up]]'' (2014), released in theaters on August 1, 2014. [[Chadwick Boseman]] plays the role of James Brown in the film. Originally, [[Mick Jagger]] and [[Brian Grazer]] had begun producing a documentary film on Brown in 2013. A fiction film had been in the planning stages for many years and was revived when Jagger read the script by [[Jez Butterworth|Jez]] and John-Henry Butterworth.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Browne|first=David|title=James Brown Estate Revs Up With Biopic|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=January 31, 2013|issue=1175|page=22}}</ref>

==In other media==
{{refimprove section|date=August 2017}}

'''Games'''
* In the video game ''[[World of Warcraft]]'', the first [[Boss (video gaming)|boss character]] of the Forge of Souls dungeon is Bronjahm, "the Godfather of Souls". His quotes during the fight are musical references, and he has a chance of dropping an item called "Papa's Brand New Bag".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wowhead.com/npc=36497/bronjahm |title=Bronjahm – NPC – World of Warcraft |publisher=Wowhead.com |accessdate=July 6, 2011}}</ref>
* A different version of "[[I Got You (I Feel Good)|I Got You]]", recorded in 1974, is playable in the rhythm video game ''[[Rock Band 3]]''. In addition, "[[Get Up (I Feel Like Being a) Sex Machine]] (Pt. 1)" is available for download across the series, while "[[Super Bad (song)|Super Bad]] (Pts. 1 & 2)" was released later, only for the third game.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}
* In the ''Worms Armaggedon'' and ''[[Worms World Party]]'' video games, many of James Brown's song titles are used in the "Soul Man" custom voice setting like "Papa's Got a Brand New Bag" or "Like a Sex Machine", clear references to James Brown.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}

'''Television'''
* Appeared as Lou DeLong in the 1987 ''[[Miami Vice]]'' episode "Missing Hours".{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}
* As himself (voice) in the 1993 ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode "[[Bart's Inner Child]]".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/the-simpsons/11296518/The-Simpsons-best-musical-guests.html|website=telegraph.co.uk|title=The Simpsons: best musical guests|author=Martin Chilton|date=Dec 17, 2014|accessdate=September 10, 2018}}</ref>
* In 1991, James Brown did a Pay Per View Special with top celebrities like Quincy Jones, Rick James, Dan Aykroyd, Gladys Knight, Denzel Washington, Mc Hammer and others attended or were opening acts. This was produced with boxing promoter Buddy Dallas. 15.5 million households tuned in at a cost $19.99.<ref>Jet Magazine July 1, 1991 pages 58-60</ref>

'''Music'''
* The songs "[[James Brown Is Dead]]" and "James Brown Is Still Alive" are all about reports on the iconic musician James Brown, and were released in 1991.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}

